1 Introduction

This RMD will cover the selection, cleaning and exploration of the basic demographic maeup of the 2007 PMS survey set, as well as the exploration of ‘Common Mental Disorders’ (SMD) amoung respondants. The prevalance of ‘Severe Mental Illness’ (SMI), will be covered in another document.

1.1 Load Source Data

# Read in 2007
source_pms07 <- haven::read_sav("pms07.sav", 
                                user_na = TRUE) %>%
  as_factor()

2 Univariate Exploration

Quick look at each variable on its own to begin with.

2.1 Age

The majortiy of respondants were in the 35 to 44 age group (19.087%),and would also be considered ‘working age’.

# Age
ggplot(data = subset_pms07, aes(x = age10yrs, 
                          y = prop.table(stat(count)), 
                          fill = age10yrs, 
                          label = scales::percent(prop.table(stat(count))))) +
    geom_bar() + 
    geom_text(stat = 'count',
              position = position_dodge(.9), 
              vjust = -0.5, 
              size = 3) + 
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) + 
    labs(title="Survey Makeup \n by Age Group (2007)", 
       x = 'Respondant Age Group', 
       y = 'Percentage', fill = 'Age Group')

3 Bivariate Exploration

3.1 CIS-R Score by Sex and Age

The total CIS-R score ranged from 0 to 49. A score of less than 12 indicated the presence of no clinically significant neurotic symptoms in the week prior to interview, and most adults (84.9%) were in this category. Among the 15.1% of adults scoring 12 or more, 7.5% were in the range 12-17 indicating a level of neurotic symptoms that was significant, but unlikely to warrant treatment. The other half (7.5%) had symptoms of a level of severity likely to require treatment. Men were less likely than women to have a CIS-R score of 12 or more and a CIS-R score of 18 or more (5.7% and 9.3%, respectively). For both men and women, the proportion scoring 12 or more varied by age. The rate was highest among those aged 45-54 (), although broadly similar to those aged 16-44, and lowest among those aged 75 and over.

More than half of adults with a CMD presented with mixed anxiety and depressive disorder. General anxiety disorder was the next most common condition, followed by depressive episode. Less than one and a half percent of the population met the diagnostic criteria for each of the remaining categories. Overall and across all age groups, men were less likely to have a CMD than women.

Rates of CMD also varied by age group: those aged 75 and over were the least likely to have a CMD. The rate among women peaked in the 45-54 age group, with a quarter meeting the criteria for at least one CMD. Among men, the rate was highest in 25-54 year olds.

3.3 Ethnicity

Rates of having at least one CMD were higher for white, black and South Asian women than for white, black and South Asian men respectively. The greatest difference was among South Asian adults.The number of South Asian women in the sample was small, so while the differences were pronounced they were only significant for CMD as a whole, and generalised anxiety disorder and panic disorder.

3.4 Marital status

Women across all marital status categories were more likely than their male counterparts to have CMD, except for divorced people, in whom the prevalence for men and women was very similar. Among men, those currently divorced had the greatest likelihood of having CMD.

3.5 Equivalised household income

People in the lowest quintile of equivalised household income (see the Glossary) were more likely to have CMDs than those in the highest quintile, with a linear trend through the income quintiles. The pattern was more marked in men than women. men in the lowest household income group were three times more likely to have a CMD than those in the highest income households. Of the individual disorders, depressive episodes showed the largest difference across income groups, especially among men, rising from 0.2% of men in the highest quintile to 6.9% of men in the lowest.

3.6 Treatment

Treatment by CIS-R score A CIS-R score of 18 or more indicated a severity of neurotic symptoms in the past week likely to warrant treatment: however only a third of this group were in receipt of any medication or counselling at the time of interview. Among those with a score between 12 and 17, 17% were receiving treatment.

Types of treatment A quarter of adults with a CMD in the past week were in receipt of treatment for an emotional or mental problem. This was mostly in the form of medication: less than 20% of adults with a neurotic disorder were taking psychoactive medication only, Less than 5% were in receipt of counselling or therapy, and 5% were in receipt of both (medication and counselling or therapy)

3.9 Employment Status and Education

More females than males reported both being in employment, or alternativly economically inactive, than men. Also of note is the high rates of mixed anxiety and depression, and depression among both male and females living within the lower income households. Of all adults employed, the common mental disorder most reported was mixed anxirty and depression. Of those adults who reported being unemployed, mixed anxiety and depressedm followed by generalised anxiety disorder were most reported. Of those adults who reported as economically inactive, the most common disorder reported was mixed anxiety and depression, followed by depression,

Of those who reported on their educational attainment, those adults who indicated no qualifications also reported the highest levels of mixed anxiety and depression, with rates for all CMDs degreasing as educational attainment increases.
